Problem 3.1 (Fitting data with error bars, 80 pts)¶

In class, we have assumed we have data of the form

\begin{align} x_i = \hat{x}_i(\mathbf{a}) + e_i, \end{align}

where $\hat{x}_i$ is the value of $x_i$ that we would expect if our model were true, and $e_i$ is some error in the measurement. Here, we have defined $\mathbf{a} = \{a_1, a_2, \ldots\}$ as the set of parameters we are estimating. For example, for Model 2b in Tutorial 3b for the linear regime of spindle length $l$ versus droplet diameter $d$, we had $\mathbf{a} = \{\nu, \gamma\}$ and $\hat{x}_i = \nu + \gamma d_i$, giving

\begin{align} l_i = \nu + \zeta d_i + e_i. \end{align}

When the errors $e_i$ are Gaussian distributed, we get a Gaussian likelihood. In the case where we do not know the variance of this distribution of errors, we took $\sigma$ of the Gaussian distribution as an unknown parameter.

In many cases, we "know" $\sigma_i$, the standard deviation associated with the error of each data point. I put "know" in quotation marks because we usually really only have an estimate of $\sigma_i$. Let us assume for a moment that we know $\sigma_i$ for all $i \in D$ and that they are uncorrelated from one measurement to the next. For the case of Model 2b (a linear function with a possibly nonzero intercept), the likelihood is

\begin{align} P(D~|~\nu,\zeta,I) = \prod_{i\in D} \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\sigma_i^2}} \exp\left\{-\frac{(l_i - (\nu + \zeta d_i))^2}{2\sigma_i^2}\right\}. \end{align}

In problem 2.3, we will think about the prior for this problem, but we will take uniform priors for both $\nu$ and $\zeta$ for now. Notice that $\sigma$ is no longer a parameter we are estimating because we already "know" all of the $\sigma_i$'s.

For this problem, we will fit Model 2b from Tutorial 3b to the data from the Good, et al. paper. We will do it in a different way though. Instead of using all data points, we will bin the data by droplet diameter and then fit the binned data, as in Fig. 1C of the Good, et al. paper.

Problem 2.1 solution¶

a) There are several ways we could choose to bin the data. The precise binning we choose in this context is less important than when we were binning histograms. There, is was important to look at the distributions. Here, are are binning more as an exercise to illustrate the trends in the data (as Good, et al. did in their paper) and to give ourselves practice with linear regression.

We will investigate a couple of ways to bin the data. First, we will choose evenly spaced 5 µm bins going from 20 to 90 µm (fixed width binning). This results in 14 bins. Five micron bins were what was used in the Good, et al. paper. This choice of bin width should capture enough points in each bin that a good mean and error bar can be calculated, but also is not too large such that the data already have a strongly discernable linear trend within the bin. In other words, we are choosing a bin width in which the noise in the data still overwhelm the linear trend.

Second, we will choose 14 bins where each bin contains the same number of points (fixed capacity binning). As we will see, the first method results in some bins having very few data points. This method alleviates that problem, but may suffer from having too much of the linear trend present within a bin. Nonetheless, this issue may be mitigated because, if the data are linear, the center of the bin should still lie on the trend line.

In the code, we will use fw to mean bins with fixed width and fc to mean bins with fixed capacity.

After we've chosen the bins, we have the issue of deciding where to place the corresponding $x$-coordinate (in this case the $x$-coordinate is droplet diameter). We could put the $x$-coordinate at the center of the bin. This works for fixed width bins, but it is not clear there a bin begins and ends for fixed capacity bins. We will therefore take the bin centers to be the mean of the droplet diameters contained within each bin.

Finally, we note that we can also compute error bars in the $x$-direction, since we have the droplet diameter data available to us.

Before we do all this stuff, of course, we have to load the data, only taking data for droplets with diameter less than 90 µm.

We see that the bin from 20 µm to 25 µm has no data in it. Obviously, we will not consider this bin. The next bin, from 25 µm to 30 µm, has only three points. From only three points, we cannot expect to reliably compute an error bar. Simililarly, the bin from 85 µm to 90 µm only has two points. We therefore will consider only bins going from 30 µm to 85 µm, for a total of 11 bins. This means we will consider bins 2 through 12. For convenience, we will define the minimal number of points in a bin for consideration to be 4.

We will now compute the bins where we put an equal number of points in each bin. This is easily done by first sorting by droplet length and then making the bin labels go as an array of consecutive 0's, consecutive 1's, consecutive 2's, etc. We have 639 data points, which is not divisible by 14. We could put 45 data in each bin and then have 9 left over. We will just randomly decide which 9 of the 14 bins get 46 data points instead of 45.

# Seed random number generator for reproducibility
np.random.seed(42)

# Use np.random.choice to pick lucky 9 bins that get extra data
extra_data_bins = np.random.choice(
    np.arange(n_bins), size=(len(df) % n_bins), replace=False)

# Set up array for bin capacity
bin_id_fc = np.empty(len(df), dtype=np.int)

# Number of entries in each bin is floor of number of data points / n_bins
n_each_bin = len(df) // n_bins

# Insert bin ids in array
start_ind = 0
for i in range(n_bins):
    if i in extra_data_bins:
        bin_id_fc[start_ind:start_ind+n_each_bin+1] = \
                i * np.ones(n_each_bin+1)
        start_ind += n_each_bin + 1
    else:
        bin_id_fc[start_ind:start_ind+n_each_bin] = i * np.ones(n_each_bin)
        start_ind += n_each_bin

We now have an idenifier for the bin that each entry in the DataFrame belongs to, whether we chose to bin with fixes edges or with fixed capacity.

b) We will now compute the most probable value for the mean spindle length for each bin, along with the error bar. We assume that within each bin, the errors in measurement come from a Gaussian distribution with unknown variance. We therefore use the methods from Tutorial 3b to compute the mean and error bar for each bin. As a reminder, the posterior of the mean spindle length for each bin, which we'll define as $l^*$, is given by the Student-t distribution, as we have derived.

\begin{align} P(\ell~|~D,M_1,I) &\propto \left(1 + \frac{(l^* - \bar{l})^2}{r^2}\right)^{-\frac{n}{2}};\\ r^2 &= \frac{1}{n}\sum_{i\in D}(l_i - \bar{l})^2; \\ \bar{l} &= \frac{1}{n}\sum_{l_i\in D}l_i, \end{align}

The error bar (standard deviation) is given by

\begin{align} \sigma_l = \frac{r}{\sqrt{n}}. \end{align}

So, for each bin, we compute $l^* = \bar{l}$ and $\sigma_l$. We will also use the same procedure to compute the most probable droplet diameter, $d^*$ and the error bar $\sigma_d$. It's cleaner to write a function to do these calculations.

In [8]: 
def bin_summary(df, bin_id, min_points_in_bin):
    """
    returns l_star, sigma_l, d_star, sigma_d for given bin_id array
    """
    # Initialize output arrays as empty lists we'll append
    l_star = []
    sigma_l = []
    d_star = []
    sigma_d = []

    # Loop through bins
    for i in range(0, n_bins):
        # Number of points in bin
        n = (bin_id==i).sum()
        
        # If not enough points, don't add it
        if n > min_points_in_bin:
            # Compute spindle length mean and error bar
            l_bar = df.spindle_length.iloc[bin_id==i].mean()
            r2 = ((df.spindle_length.iloc[bin_id==i] - l_bar)**2).sum() / n
            l_star.append(l_bar)
            sigma_l.append(np.sqrt(r2 / n))
            
            # Compute droplet diameter mean and error bar
            d_bar = df.droplet_diameter.iloc[bin_id==i].mean()
            r2 = ((df.droplet_diameter.iloc[bin_id==i]- d_bar)**2).sum() / n
            d_star.append(d_bar)
            sigma_d.append(np.sqrt(r2 / n))
    
    # Return as NumPy arrays
    return np.array(l_star), np.array(sigma_l), np.array(d_star), \
            np.array(sigma_d)

Now that we have our function, can compute the means and error bars.

First, we notice that our error bars are much smaller than those in the paper. This is because Good and coworkers chose their error bars to be give by an estimator of $\sigma$, the unknown variance in the Gaussian distribution that describes the errors in spindle diameter. This is a good choice for what they were trying to do with their plot, to illustrate the trends in the data. Their error bars gave an indication of the spread they might expect in the data. Our error bars, on the other hand, are meant to indicate how confident we are in the mean spindle length for each given bin. Because our bins each have lots of data, we are quite confident in the mean value of each bin.

We also note that the error bar in droplet diameter is almost non-existant. This is because we have chosen to compute the mean of the diameters within each bin, with the bins being fairly narrow. Combined with the large number of data points in each bin, this gives us great confidence in the mean droplet diameter for each bin.

c) As we proceed, we will assume that we "know" the error bars on each data point, as we have just calculated them. But, as we know, we only estimated the error bars by computing the posterior probability for spindle lengths for each bin. We know the error bar to the extent that the posterior for each bin can be described as Gaussian. For bins with large number of data points, the posterior is close to Gaussian, so there is not much of a problem there. Bins with smaller numbers of data have less accurate estimates of the error bars. So, we do not really "know" them and we could actually describe the binned errors probabilistically.

Another issue is that because the bins have finite width, some of the linear trend of the data will be present in the estimate of the mean and standard deviation. This presents another issue that confounds our estimate of the error.

Nonetheless, we have plenty of data in each bin, and the bins tend not to be too wide, so the binning process should not alter out conclusions too much. This is borne out in the analysis, below.

d) We perform the regression as in Tutorial 3b. The only difference is that we use the binned data and that we pass in the keyword argument sigma to give the error bars. We do have to make sure that we drop the NaNs from the fixed-width array since scipy.optimize.curvefit does not intelligently deal with those.

    return zeta * droplet_diameter + nu

We see that there is not much difference in the results for our respective curve fits. We have not computed the errors (which we will learn how to do in the next tutorial) to make comparisons in that respect.

Instead, we will compute the posterior distributions, $P(\nu,\zeta~|~D,I)$ for the fixed capacity binning and for the regression with all of the data. For the binned data, we "know" the variances of each data point, so the log posterior is

\begin{align} \ln P(\nu,\zeta~|~D,I) = \text{constant} - \sum_{i\in D_\mathrm{bin}}\frac{(l_i^* - (\nu + \zeta d_i^*))^2}{2\sigma_{l,i}^2}, \end{align}

where the set $D_\mathrm{bin}$ contains the binned data and $l_i^*$ is the most probable spindle length for bin $i$, with $d_i^*$ similarly defined. $\sigma_{l,i}$ is our error bar in the mean of the data from bin $i$.

For the regression on all the data, we have an unknown parameter $\sigma$ that describes the errors in the data. This needs to be marginalized. I.e.,

\begin{align} P(\nu,\zeta~|~D,I) = \int \mathrm{d}\sigma\,P(\nu,\zeta,\sigma~|~D,I). \end{align}

This is done on page 67 of Sivia, giving

\begin{align} \ln P(\nu,\zeta~|~D,I) \approx \text{constant} -\frac{n-1}{2}\ln\left(\sum_{i\in D} (l_i - (\nu + \zeta d_i))^2\right), \end{align}

where now the set $D$ contains all data points and $n = |D|$.

In [12]: 
# Define functions for log of posteriors
def log_post_binned(p, d_star, l_star, sigma_l):
    """
    Returns the log of the binned posterior for a single value of nu and zeta
    over all values of d_star, l_star, and sigma_l.
    """
    zeta, nu = p
    return -((l_star - (nu + zeta * d_star))**2 / 2.0 / sigma_l**2).sum()

def log_post_raw_data(p, df):
    """
    Returns the log of the unbinned posterior for a single value of nu and
    zeta over all values of d_star, l_star, and sigma_l.
    """
    zeta, nu = p
    n = len(df)
    return -(n - 1) / 2.0 * np.log(
        ((df.spindle_length - (nu + zeta * df.droplet_diameter))**2).sum())

# Function to compute log of posterior
def calc_log_post(zeta, nu, log_post_fun, args):
    """
    Computes log of the posterior over nu and zeta arrays.
    """
    log_post = np.empty((len(nu), len(zeta)))
    for i in range(len(zeta)):
        for j in range(len(nu)):
            log_post[i, j] = log_post_fun(np.array([zeta[i], nu[j]]), *args)

    # Add a constant to log_post to get it close to unity so well-behaved
    # when we exponentiate it.  We don't care about normalization.
    log_post -= log_post.max()
    
    return log_post

# Make range of nu and zeta to consider
nu = np.linspace(19.0, 23.0, 100)
zeta = np.linspace(0.18, 0.23, 100)

# Generate posteriors
log_post_bin = calc_log_post(zeta, nu, log_post_binned, 
                             (d_star_fc, l_star_fc, sigma_l_fc))
log_post_raw = calc_log_post(zeta, nu, log_post_raw_data, (df,))

In [14]: 
def plot_contour(ax, nu, zeta, log_post, y_label=r'$\zeta$',
                 title_str=r'$P(\nu,\zeta|D,I)$'):
    """
    Makes a contour plot of the posterior distribution specified by its
    logarithm, log_post.
    """
    ax.contourf(nu, zeta, np.exp(log_post), cmap=plt.get_cmap('Purples_r'))
    ax.set_xlabel(r'$\nu$ (µm)')
    ax.set_ylabel(y_label)
    ax.set_title(title_str)
    return ax

In [16]: 
# Because numdifftools functions cannot pass other arguments, make helper fun
def hess_nd(f, x, args):
    """
    Compute the Hessian of a scalar-valued function f.

    Parameters
    ----------
    f : function
        The function to be differentiated to compute the Hessian. f must be 
        of the form f(x, *args) and must return a real scalar.
    x : array_like, shape (n,)
        The arguments of f that are differentiated.  I.e., hessian[i,j] is
        d^2f / d x[i] d x[j].
    args : tuple
        Other arguments to be passed to f.

    Returns
    -------
    hessian : array_like, shape(n, n)
        The Hessian of f(x).  hessian[i,j] = d^2f / d x[i] d x[j].

    Notes
    -----
    .. This is a convenience function for use with numdifftools.
    """

    def new_f(y):
        return f(y, *args)

    hess_fun = nd.Hessian(new_f)
    return hess_fun(x)

# Compute the covariance as -H^{-1}, where H is the Hessian
hes = hess_nd(log_post_raw_data, p_opt, (df,))
cov = -np.linalg.inv(hes)

# Fetch error bars
zeta_err = np.sqrt(cov[0,0])
nu_err = np.sqrt(cov[1,1])

# Report errors with parameters
print('zeta = {0:.3f} +- {1:.3f}'.format(zeta_most_prob, zeta_err))
print(u'nu =  {0:.3f} +- {1:.3f} µm'.format(nu_most_prob, nu_err))

zeta = 0.205 +- 0.011
nu =  21.004 +- 0.644 µm

An aside: We have many data points for each bin, and we were able to compute error bars for the mean. We can also compute the most probable parameter $\sigma$, which describes the spread in the data. As I mentioned before, Good, et al., plotted this as their error bars because they wanted to illustrate the spead in the data, not their confidence in the mean of each bin.

Now, let's say we did a similar experiment, but we only took a few data points. We could use the results from the Good experiment to estimate the error bars on each of the data points in the new experiment. In this case, it is appropriate to use $\sigma$ as the error bar. Let's estimate $\sigma$ from the fixed capacity binned data. As I showed in office hours (but unfortunately did not have time for in lecture), the estimate of $\sigma$ with our usual assumptions (Gaussian likelihood, etc), is

\begin{align} \sigma = \sqrt{\frac{\sum_i(l_i - \bar{l})^2}{n-1}}, \text{ where }\bar{l} = \frac{1}{n}\sum_i l_i. \end{align}

This is calculated using the std method of DataFrames.

Problem 3.2 (Checking your model assumptions, 20 pts)¶

In Tutorial 3a, we did a check on some of the model assumptions, in particular that $V_s/V_0 \ll 1$ and that the aspect ratio $k$ is constant. Based on the analysis in that tutorial, are you concerned that a nonconstant $k$ might affect your analysis? How might you remedy the potential effects?

Problem 3.2 solution¶

While nonconstant $k$ may affect our analysis, it is certainly something we can deal with, since we measured it for every data point. Recall from Tutorial 3a the theoretical model. We have two parameters,

\begin{align} \gamma &= \left(\frac{T_0-T_\mathrm{min}}{k^2T_\mathrm{s}}\right)^\frac{1}{3} \\ \theta &= \gamma\left(\frac{6\alpha\beta}{\pi}\right)^{\frac{1}{3}}, \end{align}

with the spindle length $l$ being related to the droplet diameter $d$ by

\begin{align} l(d) \approx \frac{\gamma d}{\left(1+(\gamma d/\theta)^3\right)^{\frac{1}{3}}}. \end{align}

We could easily define a new parameter, $\gamma'$, given by \begin{align} \gamma' = k^{\frac{2}{3}}\gamma &= \left(\frac{T_0-T_\mathrm{min}}{T_\mathrm{s}}\right)^\frac{1}{3}. \end{align}

Then, the spindle length as a function of diameter is

\begin{align} l(d) \approx k^{-\frac{2}{3}}\,\frac{\gamma' d}{\left(1+(k^{-\frac{2}{3}}\gamma' d/\theta)^3\right)^{\frac{1}{3}}}. \end{align}

We see that instead of taking the length as a function of $d$, we could take it as a function of $d' \equiv k^{-\frac{2}{3}}\,d$, giving

\begin{align} l(d') \approx \frac{\gamma' d'}{\left(1+(\gamma' d'/\theta)^3\right)^{\frac{1}{3}}}. \end{align}

If we did this, there is the complication that $k_i$ is calculated from $l_i$ for each datum $i$, and we would have to be careful as to how we model measurement errors.

We can plot the data in these new coordinates. For comparison, I also include the plot of the data assuming they all have the same aspect ratio, given by the mean aspect ratio of all spindles measured.

In [21]:

# Define new log posterior function for computing error bars
def log_post_raw_data_prime(p, df, k):
    """
    Returns the log of the unbinned posterior for a single value of nu and
    zeta over all values of d_star, l_star, and sigma_l.
    """
    zeta, nu = p
    n = len(df)
    return -(n - 1) / 2.0 * np.log(
        ((df.spindle_length 
            - (nu + zeta * df.droplet_diameter / k**(2.0 / 3.0)))**2).sum())

# Compute the covariance as -H^{-1}, where H is the Hessian

cov = -np.linalg.inv(hes)

cov_fixed_k = -np.linalg.inv(hes)

# Fetch error bars

nu_err = np.sqrt(cov[1,1])
zeta_err_fixed_k = np.sqrt(cov_fixed_k[0,0])
nu_err_fixed_k = np.sqrt(cov_fixed_k[1,1])

Problem 3.3 (Priors for linear regression, 20 pts extra credit)¶

This problem is inspired by this great blog post by Jake VanderPlas.

In problem 2.1, we assumed uniform priors for $\nu$ and $\gamma$, the coefficients for the linear model. As it turns out, this is not the least informative prior. We will instead derive the least informative prior here.

a) To demonstrate why uniform priors are not uninformative in the case of linear regression, consider a line $y = ax + b$. Let's fix $b$ to be zero. Make 100 lines with $a$ going in evenly-spaced increments from 0 to 20 and plot the results. What does this plot tell you about using a uniform prior for $a$ when performing a regression?

b) The change of variables formula for a function of multiple variables is discussed in section 3.6 of Sivia. In particular, for a function of two variables, $a$ and $b$,

\begin{align} f(a,b) = f(\alpha,\beta)\begin{vmatrix} \frac{\partial \alpha}{\partial a} & \frac{\partial \alpha}{\partial b} \\[1mm] \frac{\partial \beta}{\partial a} & \frac{\partial \beta}{\partial b} \\ \end{vmatrix}, \end{align}

where the term $|\cdot|$ denotes the determinant of the Jacobian.

Use this change of variables formula and the fact that we could arbitrarily choose to define a line as $y = a x + b$ or $x = \alpha y + \beta$ to show that

\begin{align} P(a,b~|~I) \propto \frac{1}{(1+a^2)^{\frac{3}{2}}} \end{align}

is an uninformative prior.

c) Explain why incorporating this prior would preclude use of scipy.optimize.curve_fit to perform a linear regression. Why is it often still ok to use uniform priors for $a$ and $b$?

Problem 3.3 solution¶

a) This is just an excersize in plotting.

In [25]:

<matplotlib.text.Text at 0x1125ef310>

We see that higher slopes are strongly favored if we have uniform probability of picking slopes.

b) Because we could arbitrarily choose to describe a line as

\begin{align} y = a x + b \;\;\;\text{ or }\;\;\; x = \alpha y + \beta, \end{align}

we have to have

\begin{align} P(a,b~|~I) = P(\alpha,\beta~|~I) \begin{vmatrix} \frac{\partial \alpha}{\partial a} & \frac{\partial \alpha}{\partial b} \\[1mm] \frac{\partial \beta}{\partial a} & \frac{\partial \beta}{\partial b} \end{vmatrix} \end{align}

to be uninformative.

Solving the two linear equations for $\alpha$ and $\beta$ in terms of $a$ and $b$ gives

\begin{align} \alpha &= \frac{1}{a},\\ \beta &= -\frac{b}{a}. \end{align}

We can then compute the determinant of the Jacobian,

\begin{align} \begin{vmatrix} \frac{\partial \alpha}{\partial a} & \frac{\partial \alpha}{\partial b} \\[1mm] \frac{\partial \beta}{\partial a} & \frac{\partial \beta}{\partial b} \end{vmatrix} = \begin{vmatrix} -\frac{1}{a^2} & 0 \\[1mm] \frac{b}{a^2} & -\frac{1}{a} \end{vmatrix} = \frac{1}{a^3}. \end{align}

Thus,

\begin{align} P(a,b~|~I) = a^{-3}\,P(\alpha,\beta~|~I) = a^{-3}\,P\left(\left.\frac{1}{a},-\frac{b}{a}~\right|~I\right). \end{align}

We now test the expression

\begin{align} P(a,b~|~I) = \frac{1}{2(1+a^2)^{\frac{3}{2}}} \end{align}

to see if our unformative condition holds.

\begin{align} a^{-3}\,P\left(\left.\frac{1}{a},-\frac{b}{a}~\right|~I\right) &= \frac{1}{2a^3(1+a^{-2})^{\frac{3}{2}}} = \frac{1}{2\left(\left[a^2(1+a^{-2})\right]^3\right)^{\frac{1}{2}}} \\ &= \frac{1}{2(1+a^2)^{\frac{3}{2}}} = P(a,b~|~I). \end{align}

So, the condition to be uninformative holds. Note that I have included the normalization constant of $1/2$ to make it a proper probability distribution, though that is unnecessary to prove that the form of the prior is uninformative.

c) scipy.optimize.curvefit solves a least squares problem, meaning that it finds that value of the set of parameters $\mathbf{a}$ that minimizes a function of the form

\begin{align} \sum_{x_i\in D} (f(x_i, \mathbf{a}))^2. \end{align}

The negative log posterior is of this form for Gaussian distributed errors in the data and for uniform priors. If we choose the uninformative prior for a linear regression, we no longer have a log posterior of this form. We instead have (assuming all data have the same error in measurement, $\sigma$, which has a Jeffreys prior)

\begin{align} -\ln P(a,b,\sigma~|~D,I) = \text{constant} + (n+1)\ln \sigma + \sum_{i\in D}\frac{y_i - \hat{y}_i(x_i, a, b)}{2\sigma^2} + \frac{3}{2}\,\ln(1 + a^2). \end{align}

Without the last term, this has the desired format for least squares for a given $\sigma$. However, the last term ruins the functional form necessary for least squares, so scipy.optimize.curve_fit will not work.
